type":"text","backgroundColor":"transparent","index":"b0E","roundness":null,"containerId":null,"originalText":"Retrieves the map\nof keys to nodes","height":50,"link":null,"strokeColor":"#1e1e1e","fillStyle":"hachure","groupIds":[],"versionNonce":1628031077,"textAlign":"left","fontFamily":5,"lineHeight":1.25,"frameId":null,"boundElements":[{"id":"YEbcbk2kIQVfkp9MTQWZ5","type":"arrow"}],"x":1996.1671663429956,"angle":0,"y":2467.1230786344249,"width":177.53987121582031},{"seed":1058555563,"strokeStyle":"solid","id":"NNy_FGqqayRB7EGpvstRU","strokeWidth":2,"roughness":2,"isDeleted":false,"fontSize":20,"opacity":100,"verticalAlign":"top","updated":1776140909064,"locked":false,"text":"Single instance:\nRedis runs on a single server with no \nreplication. It is simple and fast, \nbut if the server fails, all data is \nlost. It is mainly used for\ndevelopment \nor very small workloads.","version":767,"autoResize":false,"type":"text","backgroundColor":"transparent","index":"b0H","roundness":null,"containerId":null,"originalText":"Single instance:\nRedis runs on a single server with no \nreplication. It is simple and fast, \nbut if the server fails, all data is \nlost. It is mainly used for development \nor very small workloads.","height":175,"link":null,"strokeColor":"#1e1e1e","fillStyle":"hachure","groupIds":[],"versionNonce":2011001797,"textAlign":"left","fontFamily":5,"lineHeight":1.25,"frameId":null,"boundElements":[],"x":1965.7180413569727,"angle":0,"y":1663.9819822327636,"width":367.80832250713138},{"seed":1119733035,"strokeStyle":"solid","id":"TnD8Ii4vJsstYQnxWQJ7k","strokeWidth":2,"roughness":2,"isDeleted":false,"fontSize":20,"opacity":100,"verticalAlign":"top","updated":1776140909064,"locked":false,"text":"Replicated setup:\nThere is one primary (master) node \nand one or more replica (slave) nodes. \nThe primary handles all writes, and \nreplicas copy the data for read scaling \nand failover. If the primary \nfails, a replica can be promoted, \nimproving availability.","version":575,"autoResize":true,"type":"text","backgroundColor":"transparent","index":"b0Q","roundness":null,"containerId":null,"originalText":"Replicated setup:\nThere is one primary (master) node \nand one or more replica (slave) nodes. \nThe primary handles all writes, and \nreplicas copy the data for read scaling \nand failover. If the primary \nfails, a replica can be promoted, \nimproving availability.","height":200,"link":null,"strokeColor":"#1e1e1e","fillStyle":"hachure","groupIds":[],"versionNonce":31765285,"textAlign":"left","fontFamily":5,"lineHeight":1.25,"frameId":null,"boundElements":[],"x":1960.9387836595447,"angle":0,"y":2019.2096049332263,"width":385.75973510742188},{"seed":1796668997,"strokeStyle":"solid","id":"gr9WxnQcnM8n-tO7d_lid","strokeWidth":2,"roughness":2,"isDeleted":false,"fontSize":20,"opacity":100,"verticalAlign":"top","updated":1776140909064,"locked":false,"text":"Cluster mode:\nData is split across multiple nodes\nusing sharding. Each node stores\na subset of the keyspace. Replicas\ncan be added per shard for fault\ntolerance. This allows horizontal\nscaling for both storage and traffic,\nmaking it suitable for large systems.","version":606,"autoResize":true,"type":"text","backgroundColor":"transparent","index":"b0R","roundness":null,"containerId":null,"originalText":"Cluster mode:\nData is split across multiple nodes\nusing sharding. Each node stores\na subset of the keyspace. Replicas\ncan be added per shard for fault\ntolerance. This allows horizontal\nscaling for both storage and traffic,\nmaking it suitable for large systems.","height":200,"link":null,"strokeColor":"#1e1e1e","fillStyle":"hachure","groupIds":[],"versionNonce":2072839813,"textAlign":"left","fontFamily":5,"lineHeight":1.25,"frameId":null,"boundElements":[],"x":1958.6941441031163,"angle":0,"y":2802.3480781457706,"width":356.17974853515625},{"isDeleted":false,"locked":false,"strokeColor":"#1971c2","link":null,"roughness":2,"groupIds":[],"index":"b0S","backgroundCo